Mahlatse Gallens and Paul Herman, News24Parliament (Netwerk24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town - A &ldquo;critical&rdquo; two-day Cabinet meeting on state-owned enterprises&nbsp;began in Cape Town on Tuesday, government sources have said.Several ministers who were due to appear in Parliament for various report-backs asked to be excused to return to the meeting.Public Works Minister Thulas Nxesi asked Scopa committee chairperson Themba Godi to be excused after&nbsp;his department&rsquo;s presentation on Tuesday.&ldquo;I have come from another critical meeting of Cabinet. We had promised to come back to that particular meeting,&rdquo; he said.Communications Minister Faith Muthambi is also said to have excused herself.&nbsp;Several state-owned enterprises, including the SABC, SAA, and Eskom have come under scrutiny after some reported losses for the past financial year.&nbsp; The SABC&rsquo;s board was unable to form a quorum after several members resigned due to the controversy over former COO Hlaudi Motsoeneng&rsquo;s reappointment to another senior management position.President Jacob Zuma&nbsp;was criticised when Cabinet announced he would lead a presidential state-owned enterprises coordinating council. It was seen as an attempt to remove the oversight of these entities from Deputy President Cyril Ramaphosa. Zuma said there was &ldquo;nothing sinister&rdquo; about the establishment of the council and such speculation was baseless and false.The Sunday Times has reported that Finance Minister Pravin Gordhan&rsquo;s Cabinet colleagues would not have been able to attend his court appearance on Wednesday. They would be in a meeting to discuss proposals to build more nuclear power plants. Charges against Gordhan and his co-accused have since been withdrawn.Ministerial vehicles glinting in the sun outside Tuynhuys for Special Cabinet Meeting this am pic.twitter.com/J3